Observation Details: Mom, dad and six owlets which fledged May 30 - June 2 and continue in the yard or in my nearby neighbors' yards. All are usually detectable 5:30-6 a.m. as they finish their night and go to bed. Pic taken at 3 p.m.-ish. I think one of these three very exposed babies was taken in the evening by the Cooper's Hawk. Two others were within 2 feet, but in cover, and the sixth was 45 yards away and well-hidden. These three had been well-hidden from dawn until early afternoon when one of the monsoonal showers approached and it got very dark, which caused the babies and Mom to leave their roosts, begin calling and Mom start feeding them again. The babies then remained exposed as is evident in the photo until the Cooper's Hawk found them near dusk.

Observation Details: *extremely remarkable, hard-to-believe, and almost assuredly a Kenai Peninsula Borough all-time high count. 10 is not a typo. Five separate pairs were carefully detected this evening, and I quite possibly had at least one additional bird, but had to play it conservatively. There was a point where I heard 4 birds vocalize within the span of 5-10 seconds. Conditions were quite good, it was peak time for vocalizing WESOs, and I put in more than 2 hours of effort quite late in the evening (starting 2+ hours post-sunset) when these owls are most likely more vocal. Yes, they will often call earlier in the night (and even somewhat occasionally during the day), but in my experience later in the night only increases the call frequency. I've been told there are papers that support this fact. In my opinion, cloudiness and moon phase have little effect on vocalization frequency of owls. Time of year, wind, precipitation, and temperature (the warmer the better) are the conditions to pay attention to (probably in an order something like that).   I was quite patient with each singing male to confirm that there was a female present as well, as she would vocalize much less frequently. Amazingly, every male was paired up. It was also notable to me that it appeared like a few of the territories abutted another pair's territory, which also caused me to take more time to make sure they weren't flying back and forth. If I didn't know better I would have assumed this species was common in the Seward area in proper habitat. I have certainly gotten the impression from old school Alaska birders that WESOs are believed to be increasing in the state, so perhaps this is another data point in that trend.  Curiously, no other owls were heard tonight. It sure seems like NSWOs have an earlier breeding cycle in this region and they are probably incubating (maybe even feeding young?) right now--which leads to considerably less frequent singing. I had several singing in this area more than a month ago.   If there are any birders looking for advice with this species, feel free to email me at: sulli.gibson@gmail.com

Locality: Wilderness Birding Adventures HQ, Fritz Creek
Observation Details: My daughter and a friend noticed a small owl standing on a pile of seine web in the yard and called me over. I was quite surprised to see that it was a Western Screech owl. A few loops of the web had wrapped around the owls right leg. I was able to free the owl and other than a few damaged feathers it seemed fit and unhurt. Owl bander Jason Sodergren came over and banded the bird and we kept it in a box until 7:45 PM when we released it in the yard. It flew off and perched for a time in an alder before flying off further into the woods.   This is the first Western Screech Owl in our yard and one of very few for Homer and the Western Kenai Peninsula. Jason's photos of this owl are here: https://photos.app.goo.gl/1AD4HFVNE9xkx6ZQ8  A Western Screech Owl that Jason caught and banded in Homer in 2015 was also a "brown morph" and looked very similar to this bird.

Observation Details: I think we confirmed only one adult (at a time) tonight, but we enjoyed great views of the two recently fledged juveniles. This evening they first appeared just north of Miles and 34th, where we got views of them in tree branches, in the open on a wire, and atop a topped-off pine (see photos & videos). They then moved to our backyard (for the 4th straight night), where we watched the silhouetted juveniles flying around and waiting for their parent to visit, while they issued their chittery juvenile begging calls. On at least one occasion the adult fed one of the juvies some small food item. The juveniles are getting noticeably more feathering and less fluffy night by night. This was a life bird for Dorna, and of course she got a marvelous photo.

Beak is dark at base and has a light colored tip. Came back later and took more photos. Photo of tracks in snow taken as it looks like the WSO landed in the powder hunting some prey. On our second visit we viewed the owl with another birder who also verified that it was a Western Screech Owl.

Literally, this was the first thing I saw this morning when I looked out the kitchen window. This is Daddy, who has become very flexible with his day-roosting as his babies get closer to fledging from their box in two weeks or so. (Mom remains in the box with them). My boy stayed there through mobbing by robins, chickadees, a Ruby-crowned Kinglet, a Warbling Vireo, House Finches and a Lazuli Bunting. But when a magpie discovered him, he took off and flew 50 yards across the yard to his safe place, the nest box he roosts in most frequently. Unbelievably, in late morning I looked out and saw him on the same branch again. This time, I noticed how intensely he was watching under one of my feeders ... and could it be ... was he ... yes! He was hunting the rat babies of the family that I haven't yet been able to dispatch as they foraged for spilled seed under the feeder. And then he dived off the branch toward the spot! Unfortunately, he missed, but now I know he's trying and needs to hunt during the day, so I'll be putting peanut butter out in the yard in an open spot near the rock wall where the rats run when disturbed. Sexed by behavior, pale bill and my boy also has a left eye problem, not as visible in these shots.

I rarely see these birds out of their boxes in full daylight, but this one flushed from the hole where he was enjoying the late afternoon sun when I let my dog out on his leash and the dog rooted around at the base of the box's mounting post. After the photo session, the bird chose to return to the box when it got mobbed by a scrub-jay. Sexed by brown color to darkest feathers (females' darkest feathers are black) and choice of nest box (he takes box "B", which I specifically installed for him to lessen how much he gets mobbed, whereas his bride always takes box "A").
Continuing.

I was called to a home to help id an owl. this appears to be a juvenile Western Screech Owl. mature feathers were just beginning to show on outer wing and front chest lacked barring and mature feathers. The owner of the  home had called Native Animal rescue as she was concerned. NAR person scared the bird and it flew out of the garage but later returned. I called Rebeca at Wildlife Services and Melanie Wortment to get info. Both felt the bird would do ok if doors were left open and the bird may try to hunt. Melanie offered to bring frozen mice and put in garage. They will be in touch. The bird seemed sedate, but also no reason to be afraid. Hard to tell what the status is.

This is Daddy, who appears on this branch at eye-level just off my deck multiple times a day. You can see he's not concerned about me less than 20 feet away because he remains fat and puffy as I photograph him. He dashes away to his nest box 50 yards away when the magpies discover him, then he reappears on the branch some time later. I saw him here three different times today. He has both an all-pale bill and a problem with his left eye (not apparent in this image) which make him identifiable. His mate and kids are still in their nest box and I expect the kids to fledge in 10 days to 2 weeks.

This is Dad. See how concerned he is about my taking his picture from about 20 feet away?
Observation Details: Babies are just about to fledge and they just might by morning. I'm pretty sure there are four as I've seen what appears to be four different babies, but I saw only two at once today. The two looked very, very funny as both stuffed themselves into the entrance hole at the same time. Dad was busy as always taking a couple different shady perches, and then tearing away across the open yard to his nest box just ahead of magpies and robins, later to show up somewhere else. It was weird and wonderful to see him just off the deck on a favorite branch when I was grilling dinner or taking his pic from about 20 feet away. Mom spent the day in bright green shade near the nest box, but about 30 feet high and getting mobbed again and again by chickadees and robins. A Warbling Vireo was scolding her when I took her picture.

We watched a Diamondback Rattlesnake for 4.5hrs off & on exploring the whole backyard. Highlights included : finding it under a pot drinking water from the just watered  plant & coming face to face through the sliding glass several times. I went to relocate looking to see if it finally left the yard at 11:13pm & heard the Owl. I called it in & you could tell it flew in right in front of us. It started responding immediately. We got pictures real quick and left it alone. We've had a box up for close to 2 years and hoping to attract it to the yard. It's been since 2020 before the road construction that we've had them back here consistently.

Observation Details: The male continues to leave his roost and sing near the female's cavity. This happened around 8:33 PM. The female responded with whinnying and then flew to a favored perch. The male soon mounted her and then they copulated for about a second or so. He continued vocalizing, more quickly, and she vocalized with a higher pitched/excited call. I was able to obtain a few images in the split second moment I was afforded. The male flew to another tree soon after copulating. The female resumed her begging-type whinny. The male brought something small for her to eat after being gone for about five minutes.

Continuing Western screech owl roosted in a huge oak tree with multiple large cavities.  I came to this area to search for Northern pygmy owls but encountered this Western screech owl by chance.  This owl seems to like to roost in two particular cavities where it can usually be seen, but I'm sure it also roosts in larger cavities in the tree where it can't be seen.  I believe this was a juvenile Western screech owl based upon the look of its feathers.  I've seen a more mature bird at this same location in the past.  I will try to post information and corresponding picture of the mature Western screech owl as well.

Locality: Kofa National Wildlife Refuge, Yuma US-AZ (33.0350,-114.1797)

Observation Details: Literally, this was the first thing I saw this morning when I looked out the kitchen window. This is Daddy, who has become very flexible with his day-roosting as his babies get closer to fledging from their box in two weeks or so. (Mom remains in the box with them). My boy stayed there through mobbing by robins, chickadees, a Ruby-crowned Kinglet, a Warbling Vireo, House Finches and a Lazuli Bunting. But when a magpie discovered him, he took off and flew 50 yards across the yard to his safe place, the nest box he roosts in most frequently. Unbelievably, in late morning I looked out and saw him on the same branch again. This time, I noticed how intensely he was watching under one of my feeders ... and could it be ... was he ... yes! He was hunting the rat babies of the family that I haven't yet been able to dispatch as they foraged for spilled seed under the feeder. And then he dived off the branch toward the spot! Unfortunately, he missed, but now I know he's trying and needs to hunt during the day, so I'll be putting peanut butter out in the yard in an open spot near the rock wall where the rats run when disturbed. Sexed by behavior, pale bill and my boy also has a left eye problem, not as visible in these shots.

Observation Details: My daughter and a friend noticed a small owl standing on a pile of seine web in the yard and called me over. I was quite surprised to see that it was a Western Screech owl. A few loops of the web had wrapped around the owls right leg. I was able to free the owl and other than a few damaged feathers it seemed fit and unhurt. Owl bander Jason Sodergren came over and banded the bird and we kept it in a box until 7:45 PM when we released it in the yard. It flew off and perched for a time in an alder before flying off further into the woods.   This is the first Western Screech Owl in our yard and one of very few for Homer and the Western Kenai Peninsula. Jason's photos of this owl are here: https://photos.app.goo.gl/1AD4HFVNE9xkx6ZQ8  A Western Screech Owl that Jason caught and banded in Homer in 2015 was also a "brown morph" and looked very similar to this bird.

*Confirmed as WESO on 12/10/18 by vocal response to tape*  Continuing bird. Was unable to see bill in morning but later (14:20) revisited and saw a mostly uniform greenish-gray bill when in the sun (the area itself is rather dark and shading is what I think is making this a tougher ID). Plumage was light gray with pronounced dark vertical strips with heavier cross bars. I believe that this birds fits well for EASO with regard to those features, though plumage is not always reliable alone. However I would love to hear a vocalization from this bird.

A number of experienced observers considered that the this bird initially reported as a WESO  may be in fact a Eastern Screech Owl because of the pale bill with greenish coloration towards the base of the bill . Subsequently David Tonneson used play back and bird responded to WESO call.

We saw the Western Screech-Owl from a distance at the entrance to its hole in a Saguaro.  Before I could get a photo of it, the owl got spooked by a bunch of dog walkers that strolled right past its Saguaro -- it moved further back into its hole and out of sight.  Later in the evening at dusk (6:38 - 6:39 PM), the Western Screech-Owl was back at the entrance to its hole in the Saguaro.  I took a few long-distance telephoto pictures of it, making sure I kept far enough away to not disturb it before it left for its nightly hunting.

Bajé de mi depa y vi algo chiquito sentado en el escalón de afuera, enfrentito de mi puerta de salida, viéndome (la puerta era de vidrio con barras de metal). Me acerqué lentamente y me di cuenta que era un polluelo de tecolotito. Salí con mucha precaución, lo levanté y buscaba sus papás, pero no se vieron ni se escuchaban. Subí a mi depa para tomarle fotos rápido y bajé de nuevo para seguir buscando los adultos. Encontré otro polluelo y los subí lo más alto que pude en un álamo, esperando que se regresarían pronto sus papás. Me fui al gimnasio y cuando regresé, no estaban. Ojalá y si sobrevivieron.

Observation Details: Baby made his or her debut today. L-R: Mom, Baby, Dad. I still don't know if more than one baby is in that box, but I suspect there's only one and I'm over-the-top happy about one. Mom was out of the box a couple times which allowed the baby some entrance hole time. Dad was out of his box at one point; I'm not sure why. Both parents left their respective boxes at 8:49 p.m. for the night, 3 minutes after official sunset. Mom made the first two food deliveries of the night by 9:16 p.m.: Two nightcrawlers. Dad made the third shortly after that, a medium-sized vole.

Observation Details: Really shocked! Pass the gate of a public but hard to find path in the back of the pond. I was identifying wrens and sparrows in the hedges when I heard a loud flap and I looked into the thick of the trees and about 6 feet up was a screech-owl that was flushed by a very unhappy squirrel. Matt and I immediately rushed home to grab Dan and we went back. We couldn't find it but we took a small animal trail into the woods and found a old fashioned stick nest where we could easily see the second owl's head. As we were observing, Matt tapped us and to our left no more than seven feet away were two more owls side by side looking right at us, perfectly camouflaged! Photographs of all the owls except for the one in the nest who ducked its head before getting a photo.

The male roosted in a very exposed place today in a dead spruce just 6 feet from the occupied nest box and caused quite a bit of agitation among the yard birds, robins and smaller (thanks to them, I went out and found him). Media notes: This appears to be the new day roost for a male I've been monitoring as he courts his mate.
Observation Details: The male that I had been watching each night with his mate for well over a week left his day roost two nights ago. The female must have followed him because she did not emerge from her known cavity last night. That was the second cavity that I had seen her use since I started monitoring their early evening activities on the 14th of this month.  Last night I went to where I suspected they may have gone based on having found a lone male several nights earlier. I did find a pair in the new location  and saw which cavity the female was using. The female of that pair left her new cavity for the night and interacted with her mate. I watched her briefly fly up to what appeared to be another possible roost/nest site, perhaps where the male had spent the day. She entered that hole, which seemed a bit large, and was back out and flying to where the male was perched within seconds.  I decided to check that spot today during daylight and found a single bird, probably the male, completely exposed at the entrance to the hole that I saw the female briefly inspect the night before. Now I know where to resume my monitoring. I hope to confirm when the female is on eggs by finally observing the male doing food deliveries to a cavity rather to the female while she is perched outside of a cavity.

Bajé de mi depa y vi algo chiquito sentado en el escalón de afuera, enfrentito de mi puerta de salida, viéndome (la puerta era de vidrio con barras de metal). Me acerqué lentamente y me di cuenta que era un polluelo de tecolotito. Salí con mucha precaución, lo levanté y buscaba sus papás, pero no se vieron ni se escuchaban. Subí a mi depa para tomarle fotos rápido y bajé de nuevo para seguir buscando los adultos. Encontré otro polluelo y los subí lo más alto que pude en un álamo, esperando que se regresarían pronto sus papás. Me fui al gimnasio y cuando regresé, no estaban. Ojalá y si sobrevivieron.

Media notes: Saw this owl outside the owl box we put up in the autumn of 2019. It seemed to be outside the owl box because there were a lot of other chattering birds in the tree. After several minutes, it flew back into the house and several minutes later, appeared at the opening. It stayed here for the rest of the day and all day the next. Weather got cooler on the 12th and it was not spotted all that day. Calling was heard the night of the 12th and in the morning of the 13th. Photo date/time: 10 April 2020, 3:30 pm Mountain time. No flash.

Observation Details: Junior fledged last night and I saw him or her in a leafy tree first thing in the morning. Mom was well-hidden within 3 feet of the baby all day and was quite fierce each time a magpie approached. Tyler visited and found Dad 20 feet away (thanks, Tyler), and in the evening, a second baby appeared at the entrance to the nest box. That was a surprise as I thought the clutch was only three and knew two had succumbed to siblicide. So much for screech-owl research that says the whole brood fledges in the same night.

Heard something hit the side of my car and figured I would turn around to see what it was. To my surprise, a small owl was standing on the side of the road just on the other side of the white line. I believe it was stunned by flying into my car. I went to go see if I could coax it further off the road or take it to a wildlife rescue place. It refused to move when I tried to shoo it away, so I went to my car to get a jacket to try and pick it up, in order to take it to a wildlife rescue center. Luckily, it flew away when I tried scooting it onto my jacket. Hopefully it was just stunned and not injured.

Observation Details: This time, I went out when there was still plenty of light out, and sure enough, he was there! Unfortunately, right when I got there, he was being harassed by a titmouse and a scrub-jay. The jay confronted him right at the entrance to his hole and he retreated inside it. After the bully birds left, he poked his head back out. Later this evening (around 7:30), I went to look at him again. He started singing while I was showing him to a neighbor. Afterwards, he flew out and left in the same direction he went last night, probably going to its hunting grounds.

Media notes: This is Mom, who has an all-black bill. This image was taken at 8:45 p.m. after she re-located, ostensibly following her baby who also relocated.
Observation Details: Junior fledged last night and I saw him or her in a leafy tree first thing in the morning. Mom was well-hidden within 3 feet of the baby all day and was quite fierce each time a magpie approached. Tyler visited and found Dad 20 feet away (thanks, Tyler), and in the evening, a second baby appeared at the entrance to the nest box. That was a surprise as I thought the clutch was only three and knew two had succumbed to siblicide. So much for screech-owl research that says the whole brood fledges in the same night.

Mom and Dad in his n' hers boxes; baby noises inside Mom's box after she left for the night and with each food delivery. Conservatively counting only one baby since I haven't seen them yet. The image below is Mom at about midday. Her feathers below and to either side of her beak are weirdly brown and I wonder if it's dried blood from a prey item. Also, she has a loose feather hanging off her beak, so this is obviously an owl with bed face.

Please remain quiet while in the area, and DO NOT play WESO calls under ANY CIRCUMSTANCES!

Media notes: Seen simultaneously at dusk, although I took this image in the morning. This bird is in nest box #2 just 25 feet from the house and got busted by the scrub-jay alarm. This bird has an eye issue with swollen eyelids to the left eye. I noticed this for the first time back in late November. The second bird was across the yard in the primary nest box that a pair attempted to nest in in 2016 and 2017. One bird was singing last evening; having two is a great sign for nesting this spring. It's interesting that this owl shows another owl "face" in the pattern of its upper breast.

Really shocked! Pass the gate of a public but hard to find path in the back of the pond. I was identifying wrens and sparrows in the hedges when I heard a loud flap and I looked into the thick of the trees and about 6 feet up was a screech-owl that was flushed by a very unhappy squirrel. Matt and I immediately rushed home to grab Dan and we went back. We couldn't find it but we took a small animal trail into the woods and found a old fashioned stick nest where we could easily see the second owl's head. As we were observing, Matt tapped us and to our left no more than seven feet away were two more owls side by side looking right at us, perfectly camouflaged! Photographs of all the owls except for the one in the nest who ducked its head before getting a photo.

Observation Details: Crazy behavior day today particularly from Mom owl. She was roosting in a tree near the nest box in the morning with an owlet occasionally appearing at the entrance to the box--normal. Late in the afternoon, Mom was in the entrance to the nest box, and she was holding a portion of a rodent in her beak. She receded into the box and returned to the entrance four times over a 10-minute period, always with the beastie, although it appeared to get smaller with a couple of returns. This was around  4:30 p.m. In the evening around 7:15, there she was again with a portion of a rodent in her beak as she perched in the entrance. The rodent was looking rather worse for the wear with portions of entrails visible. The owl remained there until 7:53 p.m. when she emerged and flew to a neighbor's tree, perching rather openly with her rodent until 8:35 p.m. Some time around there I heard the male give a soft bouncing ball sequence and also saw him perching in another neighbor's yard. Then, the female approached the entrance to the nest box twice and attempted to transfer the rodent she'd been grasping for hours to the baby in the entrance. Both times, the transfer failed. On the third attempt, the female pushed her way all the way into the box and emerged without the critter in her beak. These pictures are all the female at 4:28 p.m., 7:22 p.m., and 7:57 p.m. I've never seen nor heard of this behavior before.

This bird entered the flicker nestbox before daylight this morning, so I wasn't sure if it was an owl. However, the jays and even the songbirds have been harrassing it all day. It finally popped its head out but the jays quickly noticed and spooked it back inside the nestbox. Yard bird first!

Finally. The yard has been nearly absent of screech-owls since this year's family left on June 7. Since then, I've heard a screech-owl singing only twice and have found owl feathers in the water bowl only once. It took awhile this morning for the mad mob to discover this bird after I photographed it, but later, the box got mobbed by four chickadees, two juncos, three nuthatches and two kinglets.

Continuing Western screech owl roosted in a huge oak tree with multiple large cavities.  I came to this area to search for Northern pygmy owls but encountered this Western screech owl by chance.  This owl seems to like to roost in two particular cavities where it can usually be seen, but I'm sure it also roosts in larger cavities in the tree where it can't be seen.  I believe this was a juvenile Western screech owl based upon the look of its feathers.  I've seen a more mature bird at this same location in the past.  I will try to post information and corresponding picture of the mature Western screech owl as well.

Observation Details: Baby made his or her debut today. L-R: Mom, Baby, Dad. I still don't know if more than one baby is in that box, but I suspect there's only one and I'm over-the-top happy about one. Mom was out of the box a couple times which allowed the baby some entrance hole time. Dad was out of his box at one point; I'm not sure why. Both parents left their respective boxes at 8:49 p.m. for the night, 3 minutes after official sunset. Mom made the first two food deliveries of the night by 9:16 p.m.: Two nightcrawlers. Dad made the third shortly after that, a medium-sized vole.

Observation Details: Babies are just about to fledge and they just might by morning. I'm pretty sure there are four as I've seen what appears to be four different babies, but I saw only two at once today. The two looked very, very funny as both stuffed themselves into the entrance hole at the same time. Dad was busy as always taking a couple different shady perches, and then tearing away across the open yard to his nest box just ahead of magpies and robins, later to show up somewhere else. It was weird and wonderful to see him just off the deck on a favorite branch when I was grilling dinner or taking his pic from about 20 feet away. Mom spent the day in bright green shade near the nest box, but about 30 feet high and getting mobbed again and again by chickadees and robins. A Warbling Vireo was scolding her when I took her picture.

Heard something hit the side of my car and figured I would turn around to see what it was. To my surprise, a small owl was standing on the side of the road just on the other side of the white line. I believe it was stunned by flying into my car. I went to go see if I could coax it further off the road or take it to a wildlife rescue place. It refused to move when I tried to shoo it away, so I went to my car to get a jacket to try and pick it up, in order to take it to a wildlife rescue center. Luckily, it flew away when I tried scooting it onto my jacket. Hopefully it was just stunned and not injured.

We saw a roadkill and stopped. It was a fledgling Western Screech-Owl. There was a grove of trees at a farm house on the north side of the road. I played some tape and got an almost immediate response, including one adult flying right in overhead in broad daylight. Another was calling a short distance away, and we found two nearly grown fledglings in a tree nearby. See photo of adult bird.

Media notes: Mom roosts in the box with the baby and has an all-dark beak.
Observation Details: Baby made his or her debut today. L-R: Mom, Baby, Dad. I still don't know if more than one baby is in that box, but I suspect there's only one and I'm over-the-top happy about one. Mom was out of the box a couple times which allowed the baby some entrance hole time. Dad was out of his box at one point; I'm not sure why. Both parents left their respective boxes at 8:49 p.m. for the night, 3 minutes after official sunset. Mom made the first two food deliveries of the night by 9:16 p.m.: Two nightcrawlers. Dad made the third shortly after that, a medium-sized vole.

Observation Details: I arrived at 9:21, found the owl tree (38.437472, -105.207541; 100-ish feet north of the blue porta-potty, but viewed from the trail about 50-100 ft east of there), and watched until it appeared at 11:13.  It was overcast while I waited and the sun came out stronger just before it showed (does it only come out to sun?). Both types of jays launched a tirade around the hole just before it appeared, while a large mixed flock traversed unconcerned all around that tree. It appeared less than 5 minutes after the Jays stopped. After I walked the loop, the owl was still perched and visible at 1:32 p.m.

Really shocked! Pass the gate of a public but hard to find path in the back of the pond. I was identifying wrens and sparrows in the hedges when I heard a loud flap and I looked into the thick of the trees and about 6 feet up was a screech-owl that was flushed by a very unhappy squirrel. Matt and I immediately rushed home to grab Dan and we went back. We couldn't find it but we took a small animal trail into the woods and found a old fashioned stick nest where we could easily see the second owl's head. As we were observing, Matt tapped us and to our left no more than seven feet away were two more owls side by side looking right at us, perfectly camouflaged! Photographs of all the owls except for the one in the nest who ducked its head before getting a photo.

Media notes: Fledgling -- this is at least its 4th evening out of the nest.
Observation Details: I think we confirmed only one adult (at a time) tonight, but we enjoyed great views of the two recently fledged juveniles. This evening they first appeared just north of Miles and 34th, where we got views of them in tree branches, in the open on a wire, and atop a topped-off pine (see photos & videos). They then moved to our backyard (for the 4th straight night), where we watched the silhouetted juveniles flying around and waiting for their parent to visit, while they issued their chittery juvenile begging calls. On at least one occasion the adult fed one of the juvies some small food item. The juveniles are getting noticeably more feathering and less fluffy night by night. This was a life bird for Dorna, and of course she got a marvelous photo.

Locality: Briones Regional Park--Bear Creek Staging Area
Observation Details: As advertised!  In a hole ~20’ up in a madrone, right along the Seaborg trail on the way to the archery range.  It’s the last of 3 large madrones on the right side of the trail as you’re heading away from the parking lot ~300m from the parking lot, as the trail heads uphill after a sharp curve where it bottoms out in the wooded canyon.  If you reach the cattle gate to the pasture, you’ve gone too far.  Astonishing how it persists in this spot, with so many people and dogs passing loudly right by the tree. It’s very close to the trail, hidden in plain sight.  The hole is in a crux where the trunk splits into two major branches.  See photos. https://maps.google.com?q=37.9272579,-122.1514671

Media notes: Baby #2, who I didn't know even existed until it took the position in the entrance hole at 6:17 p.m.
Observation Details: Junior fledged last night and I saw him or her in a leafy tree first thing in the morning. Mom was well-hidden within 3 feet of the baby all day and was quite fierce each time a magpie approached. Tyler visited and found Dad 20 feet away (thanks, Tyler), and in the evening, a second baby appeared at the entrance to the nest box. That was a surprise as I thought the clutch was only three and knew two had succumbed to siblicide. So much for screech-owl research that says the whole brood fledges in the same night.

Recordist: Andrew E and Rebecca A Steinmann

Observation Details: Mom took a break from her babies today and enjoyed some out-of-the-box time until a magpie noticed her and a kerfluffle ensued. They tussled and she dived back into the box. The noise attracted a scrub-jay, two Black-headed Grosbeaks and a chickadee that continued the verbal abuse near the entrance. Later, the male shot across the open yard with a magpie in hot pursuit, and dived into his own box on the other side of the yard. Baby noises from Mom's box.

Observation Details: Boomski. And on the 11th point count of the evening, I found a pair at the Sourdough Sunrise B&B. Both birds were seen at the same time, and in close proximity for some time. Both birds were also vocalizing frequently. Please be respectful of these sensitive and obviously nesting owls.

Boomski. And on the 11th point count of the evening, I found a pair at the Sourdough Sunrise B&B. Both birds were seen at the same time, and in close proximity for some time. Both birds were also vocalizing frequently. Please be respectful of these sensitive and obviously nesting owls.

The call was very distinctive and exactly matched recorded calls on iBird Pro. Call best described as a repeated "hoo  hoo  hoo ..." note all at the same frequency but becoming more rapid at the end of the series. Very unlike the Eastern Screech-Owl's common whinny that descends in pitch as it goes.  Not wanting to stress the bird, we did not try any more photos with flash. These were all taken with a flashlight. The calls continued periodically all night and were heard the next 3 nights that we were there. Last heard calling at 7:00 am Saturday 30 March from the horse barn area.

Observation Details: Photos. I was called to a home to help id an owl. this appears to be a juvenile Western Screech Owl. mature feathers were just beginning to show on outer wing and front chest lacked barring and mature feathers. The owner of the  home had called Native Animal rescue as she was concerned. NAR person scared the bird and it flew out of the garage but later returned. I called Rebeca at Wildlife Services and Melanie Wortment to get info. Both felt the bird would do ok if doors were left open and the bird may try to hunt. Melanie offered to bring frozen mice and put in garage. They will be in touch. The bird seemed sedate, but also no reason to be afraid. Hard to tell what the status is.

Media notes: This is Mom. She has an all-black beak and a newly crumpled ear tuft. She no longer stays with the babies in the box as they're about to fledge and instead spent her day 30 feet up in a maple tree, repeatedly mobbed by chickadees and robins all day.
Observation Details: Babies are just about to fledge and they just might by morning. I'm pretty sure there are four as I've seen what appears to be four different babies, but I saw only two at once today. The two looked very, very funny as both stuffed themselves into the entrance hole at the same time. Dad was busy as always taking a couple different shady perches, and then tearing away across the open yard to his nest box just ahead of magpies and robins, later to show up somewhere else. It was weird and wonderful to see him just off the deck on a favorite branch when I was grilling dinner or taking his pic from about 20 feet away. Mom spent the day in bright green shade near the nest box, but about 30 feet high and getting mobbed again and again by chickadees and robins. A Warbling Vireo was scolding her when I took her picture.

Observation Details: I arrived at 9:21, found the owl tree (38.437472, -105.207541; 100-ish feet north of the blue porta-potty, but viewed from the trail about 50-100 ft east of there), and watched until it appeared at 11:13.  It was overcast while I waited and the sun came out stronger just before it showed (does it only come out to sun?). Both types of jays launched a tirade around the hole just before it appeared, while a large mixed flock traversed unconcerned all around that tree. It appeared less than 5 minutes after the Jays stopped. After I walked the loop, the owl was still perched and visible at 1:32 p.m.

Observation Details: Standing in water dish in our back yard to cool off.  Lives in cavity in Saguaro behind our house.  The owl came back to the water dish each evening between July 28 and August 3.

Really shocked! Pass the gate of a public but hard to find path in the back of the pond. I was identifying wrens and sparrows in the hedges when I heard a loud flap and I looked into the thick of the trees and about 6 feet up was a screech-owl that was flushed by a very unhappy squirrel. Matt and I immediately rushed home to grab Dan and we went back. We couldn't find it but we took a small animal trail into the woods and found a old fashioned stick nest where we could easily see the second owl's head. As we were observing, Matt tapped us and to our left no more than seven feet away were two more owls side by side looking right at us, perfectly camouflaged! Photographs of all the owls except for the one in the nest who ducked its head before getting a photo.

Observation Details: Appears to be a family group.  Had 3 of them perched and visible in the open, while a 4th bird was moving in the back of the mesquite.  (Not quality photos due to the dark.  Tried a flashlight for light, but created a red-eye effect and some photos had to have that processed out.  Also used a high ISO, 16000, which created a lot of noise.)

When I got out of my car one was already calling/singing, to the north. But it quieted down. No playback was used until I'd been at this location for over an hour, waiting for the SPOW. I gave one burst of Screech-owl to wake things up and that set them off. I heard them move in, eventually boxing me in, calling at the same time; 1 north (and probably the same bird I heard calling/singing to my east), 2 southwest on the hillside, and 1 up gully south. Very difficult to spot because they tended to perch within the thick oak canopy, or behind something, and their call is a little ventriloquist-like. One of the recordings attached has the possible SPOW begging call in background.

Mom, Dad, two fledged owlets, and at least one calling softly from inside the box. The two owlets fledging last night may represent an unprecedented early date in this area. Given incubation would have lasted about a month and the nestling period nearly the same, this puts the egg date in late February. Three out of four previous years in my yard saw the first fledgling on May 30, meaning the egg dates would have been around March 1. Pics represent Mom (well-hidden) and one fledgling, and Dad alone, snoozing.

We watched a Diamondback Rattlesnake for 4.5hrs off & on exploring the whole backyard. Highlights included : finding it under a pot drinking water from the just watered  plant & coming face to face through the sliding glass several times. I went to relocate looking to see if it finally left the yard at 11:13pm & heard the Owl. I called it in & you could tell it flew in right in front of us. It started responding immediately. We got pictures real quick and left it alone. We've had a box up for close to 2 years and hoping to attract it to the yard. It's been since 2020 before the road construction that we've had them back here consistently.

Media notes: Baby's first perch after leaving the nest box at 8:51 p.m. This dead aspen trunk is the first thing this owlet has touched outside the nest box. Bill-snapped at me when I approached briefly to take this cell phone shot.
Observation Details: Two parents and five owlets (so far). Three of the five fledged last night, one fledged at 8:51 p.m. tonight, and one is still in the nest box. This is probably owlet #3 in the cottonwood who fledged last night, May 30, and the other is owlet #4 just fledging at 8:51 p.m. I didn't know it at the time, but there were at least two more owlets to fledge.

Both roosting in nest box, first one came to sit in entrance hole at around sunset and stayed there for about 10 minutes slowly waking up, taking a look around, and doing some grooming.  Twice the second owl tried to push the first out of the entrance hole so that it could perch there, the second time at this was successful as the first owl flew off to start hunting for the night.  I did not want to disturb  them as they left the box so I left almost immediately after second owl appeared (I don't know if the second actually left the box or just stayed perched in the entrance, it was still in the entrance hole when I left, so that's a little less info on whether they have an active nest in the box or not).

6-24-06: Isabel nonchalantly announced, “There’s an owl in the sunroom.” I... looked and saw the Western screech owl on the top shelf out there. The back door to the sunroom was open and Gorgeous the cat was lying on the floor. The owl flew against the glass, then perched on the low florescent light fixture then on the window sill. While in the window, a Western kingbird came and tried to attack the owl through the glass! I caught the owl with a towel and held it to be looked at and photographed. The owl made a defensive clicking sound with its beak. When released outdoors the owl was mobbed by about five kingbirds and two robins.

Locality: Briones Regional Park--Bear Creek Staging Area
Observation Details: As advertised!  In a hole ~20’ up in a madrone, right along the Seaborg trail on the way to the archery range.  It’s the last of 3 large madrones on the right side of the trail as you’re heading away from the parking lot ~300m from the parking lot, as the trail heads uphill after a sharp curve where it bottoms out in the wooded canyon.  If you reach the cattle gate to the pasture, you’ve gone too far.  Astonishing how it persists in this spot, with so many people and dogs passing loudly right by the tree. It’s very close to the trail, hidden in plain sight.  The hole is in a crux where the trunk splits into two major branches.  See photos. https://maps.google.com?q=37.9272579,-122.1514671

Media notes: Moments before a Cooper's Hawk landed in a nearby tree
Observation Details: 3 flew onto the fence while one stayed in an apple tree.  A while after the other 3 moved on, it flew out onto the fence.  It was looking like it was ready to join the others when a Cooper’s Hawk started sounding from a couple of trees away.  The owl froze into the alert ‘I am bark” position and remained there unmoving even several minutes after the hawk went quiet.  It was still there when I ran out of time and had to leave.

Media notes: Unedited audio recorded with the Merlin app. The owl starts calling at 0:17.
Observation Details: A surprise bird, first detected by voice as it responded to mob track with a trill. Eventually I was able to find it, and noted that the bill looked olive-green with a paler tip, a field mark for Eastern Screch-Owl. Eventually I was able to get a recording of a quiet series of calls with the Merlin app, which I will add soon. The vocalizations were rather ambiguous, so I’m not sure what to make of this bird just yet. I will try to get more recordings this evening. Edit: after returning in the evening (see checklist https://ebird.org/checklist/S149097309), I was able to refind the bird and get a recording, which was definitively that of a Western Screech-Owl. The greenish bill is still a bit anomalous, but I will chalk that up to viewing conditions.

Observation Details: The tip of the upper mandible is light. Also, the general pattern of the underparts shows the breast and belly feathers are light with a single dark vertical shaft crosshatched by several dark horizontal streaks. with the crosshatching closer together and much narrower than that of the Whiskered, giving the bird a bolder, more distinct look than the former's muted, less obvious pattern.

Really shocked! Pass the gate of a public but hard to find path in the back of the pond. I was identifying wrens and sparrows in the hedges when I heard a loud flap and I looked into the thick of the trees and about 6 feet up was a screech-owl that was flushed by a very unhappy squirrel. Matt and I immediately rushed home to grab Dan and we went back. We couldn't find it but we took a small animal trail into the woods and found a old fashioned stick nest where we could easily see the second owl's head. As we were observing, Matt tapped us and to our left no more than seven feet away were two more owls side by side looking right at us, perfectly camouflaged! Photographs of all the owls except for the one in the nest who ducked its head before getting a photo.

I heard the begging call of juveniles and we were able to illuminate the owls as an adult was feeding a western tanager to the young. I captured some video as well that allowed more of the tanager to be seen as it was manipulated by the adult.

Observation Details: I rarely see these birds out of their boxes in full daylight, but this one flushed from the hole where he was enjoying the late afternoon sun when I let my dog out on his leash and the dog rooted around at the base of the box's mounting post. After the photo session, the bird chose to return to the box when it got mobbed by a scrub-jay. Sexed by brown color to darkest feathers (females' darkest feathers are black) and choice of nest box (he takes box "B", which I specifically installed for him to lessen how much he gets mobbed, whereas his bride always takes box "A").

Still present in the park/park vicinity.   First followed the calling to an olive tree bordering the west wall of Explorit Science Center (38.5561,-121.7098). Proceeded to walk away from that point to look for Barn Owls, at which point the WESO calling seemed to sound strangely patterned and variably distant (making me think there might be more than one). Later got a visual on a WESO in a different tree (38.5562,-121.7106) than the first, and watched that individual while listening to another 1 or 2 WESO calling from other areas. When that owl flushed, I heard some interaction calls/a duet of two owls, and eventually followed one of those to a tree at the north end of the park (38.5567,-121.7121), with the other vocalizing from farther north, in a residential area.   The whole time, I had been hearing what sounded like a very faint additional WESO calling from much farther away, on the south of 5th Street (where Kathy, Jason, Keith, and Frank all independently reported a WESO earlier this month). I never could confirm a third owl, but it seems quite possible that it was there.

I haven't done an eBird owl update in a long time. Both owlets have been out of the nest since June 20th. They fledged between one and two weeks earlier than is expected for the species. The average nestling period is five weeks, but they had been in the nest for at least a little over three weeks (though it's possible they might have hatched earlier without my knowledge). The heat that must have resulted from the constant sun exposure on the telephone pole must have prompted them to fledge earlier. After the big fiasco (which I won't go into right now) of trying to help the chicks, who I thought were in serious trouble, they quickly settled into their new life outside the nest. Here are pictures of the chicks, the adult male, and the adult female, all roosting in the same tree.
It was in this spot for at least 12 hours without moving so much as an inch
Special thanks to Jordan for allowing me to photograph this bird. The experience was greatly appreciated.

The male left his roosting box (box 2) at 8:07 and began hunting in the yard for bugs or worms. The female stuck her head out of the nest box (box 1) at 8:11. She gave several begging calls and then flew to a conifer. The male flew into the nest box immediately after she left and sang for a couple of minutes. He then left the box and flew to a conifer. Five eggs observed within the nest box while the female was away from the box. A borescope was used to quickly inspect the inside of the box.

Observation Details: We watched a Diamondback Rattlesnake for 4.5hrs off & on exploring the whole backyard. Highlights included : finding it under a pot drinking water from the just watered  plant & coming face to face through the sliding glass several times. I went to relocate looking to see if it finally left the yard at 11:13pm & heard the Owl. I called it in & you could tell it flew in right in front of us. It started responding immediately. We got pictures real quick and left it alone. We've had a box up for close to 2 years and hoping to attract it to the yard. It's been since 2020 before the road construction that we've had them back here consistently.

Observation Details: A surprise bird, first detected by voice as it responded to mob track with a trill. Eventually I was able to find it, and noted that the bill looked olive-green with a paler tip, a field mark for Eastern Screch-Owl. Eventually I was able to get a recording of a quiet series of calls with the Merlin app, which I will add soon. The vocalizations were rather ambiguous, so I’m not sure what to make of this bird just yet. I will try to get more recordings this evening. Edit: after returning in the evening (see checklist https://ebird.org/checklist/S149097309), I was able to refind the bird and get a recording, which was definitively that of a Western Screech-Owl. The greenish bill is still a bit anomalous, but I will chalk that up to viewing conditions.

Media notes: Black-chinned Hummingbird clutched in talons just prior to being delivered to a nest cavity
Observation Details: The female was already outside of the nest cavity and perched in a tree about four feet above the ground when I arrived around 9:15 PM. She went away briefly and returned to make a food delivery to the nest cavity. She emerged and disappeared again. She eventually returned to and remained inside the cavity. The male appeared around 10:07 PM with prey. He perched about 40' above the ground on a snag before taking the prey into the cavity. The prey item appeared to be chunky but not quite large enough to be a mouse or vole. Out of curiosity, I briefly illuminated the bird to capture an image that might enable me to identity the prey item. I was directly under the bird when I captured the attached image. Cropping the image revealed that the prey was a hummingbird, most likely a Black-chinned Hummingbird. I couldn't help but wonder if the hummer was snatched from its roost or possibly a nest.

Media notes: Fledgling -- this is at least its 4th evening out of the nest.
Observation Details: I think we confirmed only one adult (at a time) tonight, but we enjoyed great views of the two recently fledged juveniles. This evening they first appeared just north of Miles and 34th, where we got views of them in tree branches, in the open on a wire, and atop a topped-off pine (see photos & videos). They then moved to our backyard (for the 4th straight night), where we watched the silhouetted juveniles flying around and waiting for their parent to visit, while they issued their chittery juvenile begging calls. On at least one occasion the adult fed one of the juvies some small food item. The juveniles are getting noticeably more feathering and less fluffy night by night. This was a life bird for Dorna, and of course she got a marvelous photo.

The Screech-Owl family emerged and put on a show for the second straight evening, for us and Natsu and Hannah. Similarly to last night (see previous checklist), the two adults and two fledglings emerged from the silver maple b/w 9:15 and 9:20, spent 10-15 min. perching on the phone wires and in various trees, flying about, and calling, and then headed to the spruce in our backyard as it got darker.

Photos. I was called to a home to help id an owl. this appears to be a juvenile Western Screech Owl. mature feathers were just beginning to show on outer wing and front chest lacked barring and mature feathers. The owner of the  home had called Native Animal rescue as she was concerned. NAR person scared the bird and it flew out of the garage but later returned. I called Rebeca at Wildlife Services and Melanie Wortment to get info. Both felt the bird would do ok if doors were left open and the bird may try to hunt. Melanie offered to bring frozen mice and put in garage. They will be in touch. The bird seemed sedate, but also no reason to be afraid. Hard to tell what the status is.

Observation Details: I found the nest site in a large snag when the adult flew from a branch above me, landed on the snag and quickly disappeared into a hole in the side.  When it landed, one of the young was visible in another hole below.  Both owls retreated into the holes, but another popped out of a third hole almost immediately, multiple feet below the other holes. Based on the timing of the movements, I believe I saw 1 adult and 2 babies.  The one in the lowest hole stayed and looked at us curiously for 10+ minutes.  I showed my pictures to birders with more experience to ID it.  I’ll upload pics in case an expert has a different opinion.

Ron found a fledgling Western Screech Owl in the trees along the Sem Lane Trail.  He came to find me so that we could see it together and get a photo.  We believe this to be the first known record of a Western Screech Owl east of Highway 101. Great find Ron :)

Really shocked! Pass the gate of a public but hard to find path in the back of the pond. I was identifying wrens and sparrows in the hedges when I heard a loud flap and I looked into the thick of the trees and about 6 feet up was a screech-owl that was flushed by a very unhappy squirrel. Matt and I immediately rushed home to grab Dan and we went back. We couldn't find it but we took a small animal trail into the woods and found a old fashioned stick nest where we could easily see the second owl's head. As we were observing, Matt tapped us and to our left no more than seven feet away were two more owls side by side looking right at us, perfectly camouflaged! Photographs of all the owls except for the one in the nest who ducked its head before getting a photo.
from their actions, a mating pair.  Responded to a playback recording of a western Screech owl.  We managed to obtain a blurry picture of  a mottled grayish bird in a tree next to our car.

After the bully birds left, he poked his head back out. Later this evening (around 7:30), I went to look at him again. He started singing while I was showing him to a neighbor. Afterwards, he flew out and left in the same direction he went last night, probably going to its hunting grounds.

When I got out of my car one was already calling/singing, to the north. But it quieted down. No playback was used until I'd been at this location for over an hour, waiting for the SPOW. I gave one burst of Screech-owl to wake things up and that set them off. I heard them move in, eventually boxing me in, calling at the same time; 1 north (and probably the same bird I heard calling/singing to my east), 2 southwest on the hillside, and 1 up gully south. Very difficult to spot because they tended to perch within the thick oak canopy, or behind something, and their call is a little ventriloquist-like. One of the recordings attached has the possible SPOW begging call in background.

Media notes: High wind made all the images blurry.
Observation Details: The call was very distinctive and exactly matched recorded calls on iBird Pro. Call best described as a repeated "hoo  hoo  hoo ..." note all at the same frequency but becoming more rapid at the end of the series. Very unlike the Eastern Screech-Owl's common whinny that descends in pitch as it goes.  Not wanting to stress the bird, we did not try any more photos with flash. These were all taken with a flashlight. The calls continued periodically all night and were heard the next 3 nights that we were there. Last heard calling at 7:00 am Saturday 30 March from the horse barn area.

For the sake of the bird, I will only write that by the time I saw it the temperature had  warmed up,  probably enticing it to approach the opening but still remaining inside in the semi darkness. This is the reason for which I could not get any clear photos.

I haven't done an eBird owl update in a long time. Both owlets have been out of the nest since June 20th. They fledged between one and two weeks earlier than is expected for the species. The average nestling period is five weeks, but they had been in the nest for at least a little over three weeks (though it's possible they might have hatched earlier without my knowledge). The heat that must have resulted from the constant sun exposure on the telephone pole must have prompted them to fledge earlier. After the big fiasco (which I won't go into right now) of trying to help the chicks, who I thought were in serious trouble, they quickly settled into their new life outside the nest. Here are pictures of the chicks, the adult male, and the adult female, all roosting in the same tree.

This owl was a flattened road kill on the Douglas Highway, frozen to the pavement (ambient temperature was 19 deg F) found at 12:02 pm. It was not there the previous day, so I assume it was hit by a passing vehicle sometime the previous night or in the early morning. I retrieved the right wing and lower body of the owl (all I could dislodge from the icy roadway while avoiding passing vehicles) to verify the species identification. No head was visible. That it was an owl can be seen in the photo showing the comb-like fimbriae on the leading edge of the outer primary. The belly feathers (photo also showing tail feathers and foot) have dark crossbars on a light background matching those of screech owls. Identification was further aided by referring to the USFWS Feather Atlas for WESO (https://www.fws.gov/lab/featheratlas/feather.php?Bird=WESO_primary_adult), which shows 1) the primaries and tail feathers match the pattern and coloration of the dead owl, and 2) the lengths of the dead owl’s primaries and tail feathers are very close to those in the feather atlas: 10th primary (outer) length = 10cm, 7th and 8th primary lengths = 14cm, tail feather lengths = 9cm. Those lengths are well above lengths for Saw-whet owls; tail feathers are shorter than those of Boreal Owls.

The Screech-Owl family emerged and put on a show for the second straight evening, for us and Natsu and Hannah. Similarly to last night (see previous checklist), the two adults and two fledglings emerged from the silver maple b/w 9:15 and 9:20, spent 10-15 min. perching on the phone wires and in various trees, flying about, and calling, and then headed to the spruce in our backyard as it got darker.

The same family we have observed here the past two evenings (see previous checklists). Tonight we invited folks over and 13 of us enjoyed hearing and seeing the birds (at least 2 young and 2 adults) as they moved among trees, perched on phone wires, and perched on a neighbor's rooftop, along the street and in our yard. Apparently they roosted today not in the nest cavity but in some trees nearby, because they were first located up the street a ways by a couple who happened to be walking by. They eventually made their way to our yard, where we saw and heard them intermittently until it became too dark to see.

Observation Details: First heard adult call just at about 7:55 .  Walked toward the call where my car was parked and saw an owl land in a close tree.  With binos could see it was a fledgling.  Then a second and a third fledling landed in the same tree.  They moved around me and landed on close limbs (sometimes together and once had them forming a triangle around me). Enough light to see with my binoculars; they were bobbing and weaving and checking me out.  I stayed in the same location and just moved a couple of steps or turned my body to see them.  They were making chittering sounds and sometimes a sharp chirp.  Audio (with Poorwill in the background and a blurry photo - no flash).  They stayed around for 6-7 minutes and then seemed to move on (never saw the adult).  Amazing experience.

Locality: Powell Butte Nature Park, Portland US-OR 45.48134, -122.51259
Observation Details: I found the nest site in a large snag when the adult flew from a branch above me, landed on the snag and quickly disappeared into a hole in the side.  When it landed, one of the young was visible in another hole below.  Both owls retreated into the holes, but another popped out of a third hole almost immediately, multiple feet below the other holes. Based on the timing of the movements, I believe I saw 1 adult and 2 babies.  The one in the lowest hole stayed and looked at us curiously for 10+ minutes.  I showed my pictures to birders with more experience to ID it.  I’ll upload pics in case an expert has a different opinion.

Media notes: I thought this cavity looked good and it was the approximate location of the calls.  Through bins I thought there could be something so I took a photo and tried to zoom in on the camera screen.  It looked too dark to tell when I reviewed in the field but on the computer I lightened it and the owl was there!  You can see the right eye (closed) and the right side of the face and 'ear.'
Observation Details: I had one the previous night as well.  It started calling seemingly in response to Sora playback.

The call was very distinctive and exactly matched recorded calls on iBird Pro. Call best described as a repeated "hoo  hoo  hoo ..." note all at the same frequency but becoming more rapid at the end of the series. Very unlike the Eastern Screech-Owl's common whinny that descends in pitch as it goes.  Not wanting to stress the bird, we did not try any more photos with flash. These were all taken with a flashlight. The calls continued periodically all night and were heard the next 3 nights that we were there. Last heard calling at 7:00 am Saturday 30 March from the horse barn area.

Surprised to find when I started counting that there were four owls. After checking each one there were both adults. All were slow moving out for the night. Both adults watched the youngsters for a few minutes before flying to the water feature. Both juveniles visited various perches. They started moving towards the water but a stop on the path first. By the time I made it to the water feature 3 were in the tree. The fourth started calling and they all flew off.

By the time I made it to the water feature 3 were in the tree. The fourth started calling and they all flew off.

Tentatively this species, but bill appears to be green--like a Whiskered Screech-Owl. It is roosting/nesting in a tree cavity about 25' high in the main trunk of the Post Office sycamire.  The cavity faces down canyon.  Rene Donaldson, volunterring at the Portal Library, came out to show me the bird.

Observation Details: After sitting down for lunch under a cottonwood tree at Alden's Spring, we noticed an Anna‘s Hummingbird female was clearly agitated, calling every few seconds. We assumed we were near its nest and it was upset about our proximity. Carl investigated, looking for the nest, and found, instead, a Western Screech-Owl perched deep inside the cottonwood at eye level. He said, "well, the Anna's isn't upset about us", and showed us the owl.
